25|$|The oligopolistic {{competition}} in the British banking sector has witnessed the success of moral suasion as a monetary <b>policy</b> <b>instrument,</b> allowing the central bank to control by persuasion and directive. Given that only five major banks need to be persuaded in England, a moral suasion <b>policy</b> <b>instrument</b> is very effective because non-compliers can be immediately identified and held up for censure, while in the United States where there are many commercial banks, the Federal Reserve needs to use legalistic controls to pursue the same ends.|$|E
